hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a function $f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ that behaves differently for rational and irrational numbers. Let $\mathbb{Q}$ denote the set of all rational numbers. The function is defined by the rule:
$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
2x - 3  \text{if } x \in \mathbb{Q} \\
9 - 4x  \text{if } x \in \mathbb{R} \setminus \mathbb{Q}
\end{cases}
$$
There is exactly one point $c \in \mathbb{R}$ where this function is continuous. Determine the value of this point $c$.
